pygrametl is an 
hashtag
#opensource 
hashtag
#Python 
hashtag
#framework that offers commonly used functionality for development of Extract-Transform-Load 
hashtag
#ETL processes. pygrametl is maintained by our colleagues Christian Thomsen and S√∏ren Kejser Jensen. 
pygrametl has had a successful reach in the industry. A recent experience (https://lnkd.in/gav2Y6E) was shared by Catalyst IT (https://catalyst-au.net), a global team of open source experts that specialise in developing, designing, and supporting enterprise-grade open source solutions. 

The main strengths of pygrametl mentioned by Catalyst IT were:
1. Lots of good code examples in the documentation.
2. Clever implementation of Dimension and Fact Table inserts and updates. Migration of legacy logic and data warehouse table structure with minimal changes.
3. The framework is built on the power of python, meaning any bespoke scripting transformations are easy even for a novice python developer.
4. Easy to run on pretty much any Linux environment.

The documentation of pygrametl: https://lnkd.in/gVVBD7N
 
The paper "Programmatic ETL" by Christian Thomsen, Ove Andersen, S√∏ren Kejser Jensen and Torben Bach Pedersen : https://lnkd.in/gdHfpCb

Getting Started with NumPy:

Before you jump into data science or machine learning, it is good to have some knowledge and basic skills on certain things. When I started to explore data science, one of my lecturers told me to learn the most used packages for data science namely NumPy, Pandas, etc. So, I took an online course from Edx which really helped me to grow my skills in those packages.

Today I will share a notebook that contains the fundamentals and some tips and tricks of NumPy. This will motivate you to learn more in the data science domain. This is totally for beginners who have just started to explore data science.

These following topics are covered in this notebook:

- Rank-1 Array.
- Rank-2 Array.
- 2x2 array of zeros
- 2x2 matrix with the diagonal 1s and the others 0
- Slice Indexing
- Boolean Indexing
- Array Operations (Arithmetic, Statistical, Sorting)
- Broadcasting
- Speed Test
- Dot Operations and many more.

I hope you all will like it. Enough of talking let's jump into the notebook. Happy Hacking.

Learn how to analyze data using Python. from the basics of Python to exploring many different types of data. will learn how to prepare data for analysis, perform simple statistical analysis, create meaningful data visualizations, predict future trends from data, and more! Topics covered: 1) Importing Datasets 2) Cleaning the Data 3) Data frame manipulation 4) Summarizing the Data 5) Building machine learning Regression models 6) Building data pipelines Data Analysis with Python will be delivered through lecture, lab, and assignments. It includes following parts: Data Analysis libraries: will learn to use Pandas, Numpy and Scipy libraries to work with a sample dataset.Pandas, an open-source library, and use it to load, manipulate, analyze, and visualize cool datasets. Then  another open-source library, scikit-learn, some of its machine learning algorithms to build smart models and make cool predictions.

Hello Everybody,
I hope everyone's doing fine! 
I recently built a Telegram bot that provides you statistics on the COVID-19 Count. It generates a report, based on the country of your choice. The search currently supports almost all countries in the world. It also supports a state-wise selection for the countries of the USA, China, Italy, and Australia. The generated report contains statistics and graphical representations that provide a quick analysis of COVID-19 status of your state/country. The data is updated every day from the John Hopkins COVID-19 repository.

Any inputs on this would be highly valued.

You can also view and use the bot at @corona_count_bot on Telegram.

The bot is titled Corona Count.

Following are the Jobs involved in Task2:-
*Create and Launch Dockerfile for installing jenkins and hence set up.
JOB 1:-
Pull the GitHub repo automatically when developers push the repo to GitHub.

JOB 2:-
By looking at the code or program file, Jenkins should automatically start the respective language interpreter install image container to deploy code ( eg. If code is of PHP, then Jenkins should start the container that has PHP already installed ).

JOB 3:-
Test your webpage if it is working or not.

JOB 4:-
If the webpage is not working, then send an email to the developer with error messages.

JOB 5:-
If the container where the app is running fails due to any reason then this job should automatically start the container again.

Reliable data is crucial for Data Scientist, Data Analyst, and Machine Learning Engineers. If you want to analyze a company, the first step is to find the data from different sources. Now you don't know how reliable and genuine the data is. Even if it is uploaded on Kaggle, it is still uploaded by some XYZ user.

For example, recently I was trying to analyze the worldwide data of coronavirus and I found out that many of the sources were not reliable.

One of the solutions to this problem is Web Scraping. Instead of relying on some random data, you can simply generate your own data from the official websites and that's the primary reason I took this course "Web Scraping Using Python"

The second reason is the lack of data. We might be familiar with how easy it is to access open-source databases from international companies such as Amazon and Apple. But what if you want to analyze a local company and there is no data available? That's where Web Scraping comes in!

Note: I have found a few glitches in the course, if anyone wishes to learn Web Scrapping from scratch can DM me!

Thank You!
